  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I prevent iMovie for iPad from cropping the top and bottom off my video that was originally taken in portrait orientation?",
  "response": "When you import a portrait (vertical) video into iMovie for iPad, the app often defaults to fitting the video into a landscape (horizontal) frame, which can result in the top and bottom being cropped. Here\u2019s how you can prevent this and maintain the full portrait orientation of your video:\n\n### Method 1: Use the Pinch-to-Zoom Feature\n1. **Start a New Project**: Open iMovie and create a new project.\n2. **Add Your Video**: Select the portrait video you want to use.\n3. **Pinch to Adjust the Frame**: In the timeline, tap the video clip to select it. Then, use a pinch gesture on the preview screen to zoom out. This will reveal more of the top and bottom of the video.\n4. **Refine the Position**: Drag the video up or down in the frame to ensure the important parts are visible.\n\n### Method 2: Add a Letterbox Effect (Black Bars)\n1. **Create a New Project**: Open iMovie and start a new project.\n2. **Add Your Video**: Import your portrait video.\n3. **Use a Blank Background**: Add a blank background (like a black image) to your project.\n4. **Insert Your Video as a Picture-in-Picture (PiP)**: Highlight your video, tap the \"...\" (more) button, and select **Picture in Picture**. Place it in the center of the black background.\n5. Adjust the size and position of the PiP frame to fit your portrait video without cropping.\n\n### Method 3: Use a Third-Party App to Rotate the Video\nIf iMovie\u2019s cropping is too restrictive, you can use a third-party app to rotate your video to landscape format before importing it into iMovie. This way, the video will fill the frame without cropping. Apps like **Rotate Video** or **Video Rotate & Flip** can do this quickly. Once rotated, import the video into iMovie.\n\n### Method 4: Export Without Cropping\nIf you\u2019re exporting a project and notice it\u2019s cropped, try these steps:\n1. **Adjust Zoom**: Make sure your video isn\u2019t zoomed in too much in the preview window.\n2. **Export Settings**: When exporting, ensure the resolution and aspect ratio match your original video.\n\nBy following these methods, you should be able to preserve the full portrait orientation of your video in iMovie for iPad.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
